list_page_teaser: Norma and Nadine are the natural bosses in this group, with Shelly, Bobby, and Ed being the ones willing to go with the flow.  Click to learn more!
description_html:
These spiritual portraits are all fairly colorful, showing that this group of people are a fairly flexible, normal bunch. The Red in Norma's image shows she's a warm, gentle boss, and the Yellow shows she's realistic.

The images of the two couples — Shelly and Bobby, and Big Ed and Nadine — show that each pair has similarities and differences. Their similarities enable them to get along well, while their differences help keep thier relationships interesting and dynamic.
story_html:
The Yellow in Shelly's and Bobby's portraits show both of them are realistic and open to new experiences — which can help to explain how they can carry on their affair with little concern for morality, but a very real fear of getting caught. Meanwhile, the Red in Shelly's image contrasts with the Green in Bobby's, showing they are different enough to make things interesting.

The Blue and Yellow in Big Ed's portrait shows he's open to both new experiences and new ideas, and the Red shows he's amiable. These qualities help explain how he can continue to stand by and get along with his wife Nadine.

Ed's and Nadine's portraits are the only ones in this gallery to have a significant amount of Blue. The Blue in Nadine's image shows her preference for ideas is stronger than Ed's, and she is definitely someone whose ideas can be a little off-beat.

image_list.title: Norma Jennings
image_list.subtitle_html: Owner and Manager of the Double R Diner
image_list.gallery_page_teaser: Norma Jennings's spiritual portrait shows she is outgoing, friendly, and down-to-earth.  Click on the image to learn more!
image_list.explain_dom: The Red in this spiritual portrait represents Norma's dominant personality trait, her warmth, friendliness, and compassion.  In Extraverts, the dominant trait is directed outwardly, and spiritual portraits use a long vertical line to represent this, because it is the side of their personality that is most evident.
image_list.explain_aux: The Yellow in this spiritual portrait represents Norma's auxiliary personality trait, her realistic, down-to-earth outlook.  In Extraverts, the auxiliary trait is directed inwardly, and spiritual portraits use a horizontal line to represent this.

In Extraverts, the dominant trait is directed outwardly, and spiritual portraits use a long vertical line to represent this, because it is the side of their personality that is most evident.
image_list.explain_aux: The Red in this spiritual portrait represents Shelly's auxiliary personality trait, her passion, friendliness, and warmth.  In Extraverts, the auxiliary trait is directed inwardly, and spiritual portraits use a horizontal line to represent this.

image_list.title: 'Big Ed' Hurley

image_list.gallery_page_teaser: 'Big Ed' Hurley's spiritual portrait shows he is outgoing, warm and friendly, and very open to new experiences and ideas.  Click on the image to learn more!
image_list.explain_dom: The Yellow in this spiritual portrait represents Big Ed's dominant personality trait, his realistic outlook and openness to new experiences.  In Extraverts, the dominant trait is directed outwardly, and spiritual portraits use a long vertical line to represent this, because it is the side of their personality that is most evident.  Ed's image also has a lot of Blue, indicating he is also open to new ideas, which helps him get along with Nadine.
